4 SYNOPSIS:
5 This bill would create the Alabama Geographic
6 Information Executive Council (GIS Council) and the
7 Alabama Geographic Information Program Office (GIS
8 Office), already in existence by Executive Order of the
9 Governor, to be the coordinating authority for the
10 collection of geographic information system (GIS) data
11 in the State of Alabama.
12 This bill would further provide for coordination
13 between the GIS Office, as operating arm of the GIS
14 Council, and the 911 Board, recognizing that the GIS
15 Office is the central repository for statewide GIS data
16 while the 911 Board is authorized to gather and
17 maintain the accuracy of GIS data for the provision of
18 emergency 911 services.
19
20 A BILL
21 TO BE ENTITLED
22 AN ACT
23
24 Relating to geographic information technology; to add
25 Chapter 27A, commencing with Section 41-27A-1, to Title 41 of
26 the Code of Alabama 1975, to establish the Alabama Geographic
27 Information Executive Council, the Alabama Geographic
28 Information Program Office, the State of Alabama Geographic
Page 1

Information Program Office, the State of Alabama Geographic
HB97 INTRODUCED
29 Information Officer, and an advisory committee; and to provide
30 for coordination between the Alabama Geographic Information
31 Executive Council and Alabama Geographic Information Program
32 Office with the 911 Board; to amend Section 11-98-4.1, Code of
33 Alabama 1975, to further provide for the authority of the 911
34 Board to compile and maintain geographic information system
35 data for emergency 911 services; and to make nonsubstantive,
36 technical revisions to update existing code language to
37 current style.
38 BE IT ENACTED BY THE LEGISLATURE OF ALABAMA:
39 Section 1. Chapter 27A, commencing with Section
40 41-27A-1, is added to Title 41 of the Code of Alabama 1975, to
41 read as follows:
42 §41-27A-1
43 The Legislature finds all of the following:
44 (1) The development, use, and sharing of geographic
45 information, geospatial data, and the efficient use of
46 geographic information system (GIS) technology are yielding
47 sustained, long-term benefits to the people of Alabama, with
48 innumerable applications that serve economic development,
49 enhance governmental operations, protect natural resources,
50 and simplify human activity.
51 (2) Because public agencies expend considerable
52 resources collecting and managing geographic information in
53 diverse formats and scales, it is necessary to require
54 coordination and direction in the development and
55 implementation of GIS to continually improve the delivery of
56 public services, to reduce redundancy and duplication of
Page 2

public services, to reduce redundancy and duplication of
HB97 INTRODUCED
57 effort, and to prevent the spread of erroneous geographic
58 information in activities that demand urgency such as
59 emergency response.
60 (3) The management and coordination of GIS is currently
61 entrusted to the Alabama Geographic Information Executive
62 Council, the Alabama Geographic Information Program Office,
63 and the Advisory Committee, all created by executive order.
64 (4) The 911 Board, and by extension the local emergency
65 communication districts, are charged by legislative act with
66 the "efficient and effective delivery" of enhanced 911
67 service, a duty that explicitly requires the collection and
68 remediation of geospatial information into GIS mapping.
69 (5) The Legislature wishes to enable formal
70 coordination between the Alabama Geographic Information
71 Program Office, as the operating arm of the Alabama Geographic
72 Information Executive Council, and the 911 Board, while
73 maintaining the boundaries of their authorized duties and
74 functions.
75 §41-27A-2
76 (a) The Alabama Geographic Information Executive
77 Council (Executive Council) is established as an independent
78 council to develop policies regarding the use of geographic
79 information, geographic information systems (GIS), and other
80 related technologies, to include all of the following
81 responsibilities:
82 (1) Strategic planning for a sustainable state program
83 for GIS.
84 (2) Resolution of policy and technology issues.
